04576nam a22007095i 9780691186719DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20181998nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911867197 a10.1515/97806911867192doi  a(DE-B1597)501849  a(OCoLC)1076439665  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHM101b.R56 1998eb 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a3062221 aRochon, Thomas R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCulture Moves :bIdeas, Activism, and Changing Values /cThomas R. Rochon. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tTables -- tPreface -- tData Sources -- tPart One Theoretical Perspective -- tChapter 1. Adaptation in Human Communities -- tChapter 2. Critical Communities and Movements -- tChapter 3. The Acceptance of New Cultural Values -- tPart Two Microfoundations -- tChapter 4. The Creation of Solidarity -- tChapter 5. Political Engagement -- tPart Three Social and Political Structures -- tChapter 6. Diffusion of Change in Society -- tChapter 7. Political and Social Alliances -- tChapter 8. Advancing Our Understanding of Cultural Change -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSome periods in history are marked by stability in cultural values; at other times, values undergo rapid change. How and why do cultural transformations, such as those affecting race and gender relations, take place? How does one value win acceptance in society when there are conflicting values competing for attention? In Culture Moves, Thomas Rochon addresses this complex process and develops a theory to explain both how values originate and how they spread. In particular, he analyzes the crucial role that small communities of critical thinkers play in developing new ideas and inspiring their dissemination through larger social movements. Rochon develops this theory by drawing from such sources as survey research, content analysis of the mass media, and historical accounts. He focuses mainly on contemporary issues in the United States--such as feminism, civil rights, and environmentalism--but also discusses cases ranging from the French Revolution to the abolition of slavery. He explores the cultural niches--typically universities and research institutes--where new ideas and values evolve and then traces how these ideas play out in society through movements that may have little formal structure. Attention in the media, he argues, is often a deciding move in the contest over public opinion. This book will fundamentally revise how we understand the process of social change and what the prospects are for particular culture moves in the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCulture. 0aSocial change. 0aSocial movements. 0aSocial values. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691186719zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691186719423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691186719.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK